8
00:00:21.930 --> 00:00:25.320
Things make more sense to me when I understand why.

9
00:00:25.320 --> 00:00:28.023
This is kind of like the why lecture of geriatrics.

10
00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:33.033
Why is it things affect older adults differently?

11
00:00:34.350 --> 00:00:35.913
So we're gonna get into that,

12
00:00:37.470 --> 00:00:39.510
and every time the Beers Criteria gets updated,

13
00:00:39.510 --> 00:00:44.510
it's like Christmas for folks who practice geriatrics.

14
00:00:44.550 --> 00:00:47.073
And it was updated a couple of years ago now.

15
00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:50.610
So we'll tie into some of that.

16
00:00:50.610 --> 00:00:55.610
Now, let's get into some of the problems first.

17
00:00:57.150 --> 00:00:58.950
This is a little bit of an older slide

18
00:00:58.950 --> 00:01:01.980
that I've been using and I inherited from somebody,

19
00:01:01.980 --> 00:01:06.660
but the difference, these particular cardiovascular drugs,

20
00:01:06.660 --> 00:01:11.490
who's getting studied, the ages that are in studies,

21
00:01:11.490 --> 00:01:14.973
and then the ages of folks getting treatment.

22
00:01:15.960 --> 00:01:19.110
So most folks in studies are younger, they're healthier,

23
00:01:19.110 --> 00:01:22.470
but the medicines that we use are applied

24
00:01:22.470 --> 00:01:24.183
to older adults, okay?

25
00:01:26.190 --> 00:01:27.813
Now this is some newer data.

26
00:01:29.310 --> 00:01:31.020
Who's in studies?

27
00:01:31.020 --> 00:01:34.463
The light blue is folks older than 65, okay?

28
00:01:36.510 --> 00:01:37.650
Oh, it gets even better.

29
00:01:37.650 --> 00:01:42.390
The next slide is delightful, okay?

30
00:01:42.390 --> 00:01:43.690
I can see your excitement.

31
00:01:45.810 --> 00:01:49.440
Here it is even specific conditions.

32
00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:51.900
It breaks it down, all these common things we do,

33
00:01:51.900 --> 00:01:53.853
insomnia, heart failure,

34
00:01:54.990 --> 00:01:59.913
AFib, osteoporosis, diabetes, okay?

35
00:02:01.170 --> 00:02:02.460
So younger people in studies,

36
00:02:02.460 --> 00:02:05.910
and then they're being applied to these new medications

37
00:02:05.910 --> 00:02:09.570
to older adults who are on multiple medicines

38
00:02:09.570 --> 00:02:11.130
and chronic conditions and all that.

39
00:02:11.130 --> 00:02:14.920
Okay, so that's also the beauty of geriatrics

40
00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:18.027
'cause it all comes down to the person in front of you,

41
00:02:18.027 --> 00:02:21.030
and the art of medicine really matters.

42
00:02:21.030 --> 00:02:23.400
And as family doctors, we're good at that.

43
00:02:23.400 --> 00:02:24.720
We're good at the science,

44
00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:26.760
but we're also really good at relationships

45
00:02:26.760 --> 00:02:29.010
and finding out what our patient's goals are.

46
00:02:30.300 --> 00:02:31.770
So here's our question.

47
00:02:31.770 --> 00:02:35.520
Which of the following pharmacokinetic factors

48
00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:39.363
changes the least with age?

49
00:02:42.120 --> 00:02:43.173
The least.

50
00:02:48.510 --> 00:02:49.623
Let's see how we did.

51
00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:54.420
Oh, all right.

52
00:02:54.420 --> 00:02:55.253
Okay.

53
00:02:56.730 --> 00:02:57.720
Let's start over.

54
00:02:57.720 --> 00:02:58.553
No, just kidding.

55
00:02:58.553 --> 00:02:59.386
This is tough.

56
00:02:59.386 --> 00:03:00.219
These are tough questions,

57
00:03:00.219 --> 00:03:01.426
especially this late in the afternoon.

58
00:03:01.426 --> 00:03:04.110
Actually, absorption changes the least

59
00:03:04.110 --> 00:03:07.233
as people get older, okay?

60
00:03:08.190 --> 00:03:10.800
Everything else changes pretty considerably.

61
00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:11.910
That's why medications

62
00:03:11.910 --> 00:03:15.150
affect older adults differently, okay?

63
00:03:15.150 --> 00:03:16.830
And then it becomes even more complicated.

64
00:03:16.830 --> 00:03:18.450
I mean, this is a really tough question

65
00:03:18.450 --> 00:03:19.380
at this point in the afternoon.

66
00:03:19.380 --> 00:03:21.180
You got an 80-year-old hypertensive woman switched

67
00:03:21.180 --> 00:03:22.376
from atenolol to propranolol

68
00:03:22.376 --> 00:03:24.744
'cause trying to kill two birds with one stone.

69
00:03:24.744 --> 00:03:25.980
She's got a tremor.

70
00:03:25.980 --> 00:03:28.860
A week later, she's more bradycardic, confused, despondent.

71
00:03:28.860 --> 00:03:31.060
Most likely cause is which of the following?

72
00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:38.880
Boom, look at that. (laughs)

73
00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:41.040
Yeah, lipophilia of propranolol.

74
00:03:41.040 --> 00:03:44.043
So even within certain classes of medicines,

75
00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:48.753
they're gonna affect folks differently, okay?

76
00:03:50.640 --> 00:03:54.123
You think older adults have more or less fat?

77
00:03:57.600 --> 00:04:00.293
They lose muscle, they're gonna have more fat, okay?

78
00:04:04.170 --> 00:04:06.663
Less protein, we'll get into this, okay?

79
00:04:07.950 --> 00:04:09.663
So changes with aging.

80
00:04:11.130 --> 00:04:12.960
I'm gonna be very open and honest with y'all.

81
00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:14.403
I am 43 years old.

82
00:04:15.330 --> 00:04:17.103
February is my birthday month.

83
00:04:18.840 --> 00:04:20.973
When you reach your mid 30s,

84
00:04:22.500 --> 00:04:26.663
naturally your creatinine clearance starts to decline, okay?

85
00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:30.730
And that's gonna continue throughout your life.

86
00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:33.690
Same thing with...

87
00:04:33.690 --> 00:04:37.500
It really is remarkable the amount of muscle mass,

88
00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:40.830
muscle explosiveness that we lose too

89
00:04:40.830 --> 00:04:43.173
when we start to be 40 years old,

90
00:04:44.100 --> 00:04:46.113
and that compounds every year.

91
00:04:47.940 --> 00:04:52.440
That's why resistance training exercise are so important

92
00:04:52.440 --> 00:04:54.483
to maintain independence, okay?

93
00:04:57.120 --> 00:04:59.160
So absorption-minimally changed.

94
00:04:59.160 --> 00:05:04.160
Distribution, we talk more fat, less muscle.

95
00:05:07.050 --> 00:05:10.338
Metabolism over time, naturally, the liver shrinks.

96
00:05:10.338 --> 00:05:12.093
There's less blood flow.

97
00:05:13.650 --> 00:05:16.980
It's probably been a long time since we thought about this

98
00:05:16.980 --> 00:05:19.200
since we're in medical school,

99
00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:21.543
phase one and phase two metabolism.

100
00:05:23.220 --> 00:05:24.450
I've been picking on the residents.

101
00:05:24.450 --> 00:05:25.283
They're probably closer to this

102
00:05:25.283 --> 00:05:28.290
and remember it better than the rest of us.

103
00:05:28.290 --> 00:05:31.263
Phase one is affected more than phase two.

104
00:05:32.430 --> 00:05:34.080
So medicines that go through phase one

105
00:05:34.080 --> 00:05:36.280
are gonna be a bigger deal for older adults.

106
00:05:37.198 --> 00:05:40.380
Got an 84 year old man, less alert, balance deteriorating.

107
00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:44.250
He was taking five milligrams of diazepam twice a day

108
00:05:44.250 --> 00:05:46.260
and agrees to stop.

109
00:05:46.260 --> 00:05:47.640
One week later, he's no better.

110
00:05:47.640 --> 00:05:49.623
Three weeks later, he's improved.

111
00:05:53.550 --> 00:05:54.843
Why did this happen?

112
00:05:56.490 --> 00:05:57.810
Withdrew the drug too quickly,

113
00:05:57.810 --> 00:06:01.350
active drug metabolites, increased receptor sensitivity,

114
00:06:01.350 --> 00:06:03.839
or (chuckles) patient didn't listen to you

115
00:06:03.839 --> 00:06:06.480
and just kept on taking the medicine?

116
00:06:06.480 --> 00:06:07.443
They were lying.

117
00:06:09.330 --> 00:06:10.383
That never happens.

118
00:06:16.638 --> 00:06:19.170
Yeah, yeah, very nice.

119
00:06:19.170 --> 00:06:21.480
This gets into even within certain classes of medicines,

120
00:06:21.480 --> 00:06:24.090
diazepam is gonna be more reliant

121
00:06:24.090 --> 00:06:29.090
on that phase one metabolism as opposed to lorazepam,

122
00:06:29.610 --> 00:06:32.430
which is more dependent on phase two.

123
00:06:32.430 --> 00:06:34.530
So that would probably be a safer choice,

124
00:06:34.530 --> 00:06:37.083
the lorazepam, if you're gonna use something, okay?

125
00:06:39.630 --> 00:06:42.513
There are only two safe medicines in geriatrics.

126
00:06:48.060 --> 00:06:49.320
I'll tell you.

127
00:06:49.320 --> 00:06:54.320
Tylenol and Colace, and Colace doesn't work, okay?

128
00:06:55.147 --> 00:06:56.820
(audience laughs)

129
00:06:56.820 --> 00:07:01.323
Everything else is gonna have a risk to it, all right?

130
00:07:02.730 --> 00:07:05.973
So diazepam would be a big no-no medicine.

131
00:07:08.490 --> 00:07:10.950
A lot of questions, keep you all engaged.

132
00:07:10.950 --> 00:07:13.173
Which one changes the most with age,

133
00:07:14.400 --> 00:07:17.703
absorption, distribution, metabolism, elimination?

134
00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:24.450
It's elimination.

135
00:07:24.450 --> 00:07:26.220
That's the biggest factor,

136
00:07:26.220 --> 00:07:28.380
that clearance of medications.

137
00:07:28.380 --> 00:07:31.950
All back to that creatinine clearance decreasing with age.

138
00:07:31.950 --> 00:07:34.560
Now, a lot of people, a common question I get

139
00:07:34.560 --> 00:07:36.780
with this lecture is, which matters more,

140
00:07:36.780 --> 00:07:39.213
GFR or creatinine clearance?

141
00:07:40.860 --> 00:07:41.913
It depends.

142
00:07:43.380 --> 00:07:45.600
I'm a family doctor, so I'm very simple.

143
00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:50.340
It depends on what the medication was studied for, okay?

144
00:07:50.340 --> 00:07:53.310
So you're gonna have to have your resource ready to go.

145
00:07:53.310 --> 00:07:56.070
Some medicines are dosed based on creatinine clearance.

146
00:07:56.070 --> 00:07:57.633
Some are based on GFR.

147
00:07:58.620 --> 00:08:01.380
You gotta start being familiar with that.

148
00:08:01.380 --> 00:08:04.397
We should get used

149
00:08:04.397 --> 00:08:08.160
to calculating creatinine clearance though, okay?

150
00:08:08.160 --> 00:08:10.050
Usually we get a BMP CMP

151
00:08:10.050 --> 00:08:13.800
It calculates the GFR eGFR for us.

152
00:08:13.800 --> 00:08:16.888
Creatinine clearance, we've gotta pull up on our phone

153
00:08:16.888 --> 00:08:18.005
and our favorite calculator

154
00:08:18.005 --> 00:08:20.343
and just plug in the numbers, okay?

155
00:08:21.330 --> 00:08:22.740
Which one of these folks do you think

156
00:08:22.740 --> 00:08:24.390
has a lower creatinine clearance?

157
00:08:25.500 --> 00:08:27.990
Got a 50 year old woman, 150 pounds.

158
00:08:27.990 --> 00:08:29.490
Creatinine comes back 2.2.

159
00:08:29.490 --> 00:08:31.490
That's gonna catch our attention, right?

160
00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:35.880
Or we got an 80 year old woman, 110 pounds.

161
00:08:35.880 --> 00:08:37.560
Serum creatinine is 1.4.

162
00:08:37.560 --> 00:08:40.590
We think, ah, you know, ah, you know what?

163
00:08:40.590 --> 00:08:41.670
Maybe.

164
00:08:41.670 --> 00:08:43.820
Maybe I gotta pay attention to that or not.

165
00:08:45.570 --> 00:08:50.340
Depends on if it's late in the afternoon, okay?

166
00:08:50.340 --> 00:08:52.170
Which one is worse?

167
00:08:52.170 --> 00:08:54.060
It's gonna be that 80 year old.

168
00:08:54.060 --> 00:08:55.170
Look at that.

169
00:08:55.170 --> 00:08:58.020
All of a sudden they're below 30,

170
00:08:58.020 --> 00:09:01.770
and that's a cutoff for a lot of medication changes, okay?

171
00:09:01.770 --> 00:09:03.790
Because you take weight and age

172
00:09:04.800 --> 00:09:07.260
into effect for the Cockroft-Gault calculation.

173
00:09:07.260 --> 00:09:11.493
Do not memorize this equation, okay?

174
00:09:13.110 --> 00:09:17.964
If that's on your exam, that's wrong.

175
00:09:17.964 --> 00:09:19.590
(audience laughs)

176
00:09:19.590 --> 00:09:22.803
Send them a letter and complain about it, okay?

177
00:09:26.070 --> 00:09:27.173
You know, we've noticed this.

178
00:09:27.173 --> 00:09:28.500
If this has happened to you before,

179
00:09:28.500 --> 00:09:30.153
you get a BMP or a CMP on somebody

180
00:09:30.153 --> 00:09:32.880
and the creatinine comes back, it's low,

181
00:09:32.880 --> 00:09:36.033
or maybe it's even sometimes like too low to calculate,

182
00:09:37.020 --> 00:09:38.700
you've seen that before?

183
00:09:38.700 --> 00:09:39.753
Why does that happen?

184
00:09:41.465 --> 00:09:43.200
(audience member chatters)

185
00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:44.340
Where's creatinine come from?

186
00:09:44.340 --> 00:09:46.380
Muscle, right?

187
00:09:46.380 --> 00:09:48.600
If they're frail and older, they don't have enough muscle

188
00:09:48.600 --> 00:09:50.970
to break down to get in the bloodstream

189
00:09:50.970 --> 00:09:52.440
to really have a significant...

190
00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:55.443
So we always overestimate the creatinine clearance.

191
00:09:57.270 --> 00:09:59.790
And those of you who are in your mid 30s,

192
00:09:59.790 --> 00:10:01.113
the decline has started.

193
00:10:02.400 --> 00:10:05.250
80 year old on warfarin, INR 2.5.

194
00:10:05.250 --> 00:10:07.140
Best explanation for increased bleeding risk

195
00:10:07.140 --> 00:10:10.140
compared to a younger patient is,

196
00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:12.000
difference in elimination, metabolism,

197
00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.723
volume of distribution, or pharmacodynamic differences?

198
00:10:20.940 --> 00:10:22.893
See, all these questions are hard.

199
00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.910
We should do this lecture first thing in the morning

200
00:10:26.910 --> 00:10:27.960
when you have coffee.

201
00:10:29.820 --> 00:10:32.190
So let's get into this just in case these show up

202
00:10:32.190 --> 00:10:34.350
on your exam, okay?

203
00:10:34.350 --> 00:10:36.570
Pharmacokinetics, those are the elimination,

204
00:10:36.570 --> 00:10:37.980
absorption, metabolism.

205
00:10:37.980 --> 00:10:39.870
That's what the body does to the drug.

206
00:10:39.870 --> 00:10:42.470
Pharmacodynamics, that's what the drug's gonna do

207
00:10:42.470 --> 00:10:43.303
to the body.

208
00:10:43.303 --> 00:10:46.203
The Coumadin, it's gonna increase bleeding risk, okay?

209
00:10:47.580 --> 00:10:49.530
Elderly are at greater risk

210
00:10:49.530 --> 00:10:52.560
because they're more likely

211
00:10:52.560 --> 00:10:54.510
to have some of these bad events, okay?

212
00:10:55.948 --> 00:10:58.348
So if you get these simple definition questions,

213
00:10:59.880 --> 00:11:02.550
knock it out, get the question right,

214
00:11:02.550 --> 00:11:03.900
then forget what they mean.

215
00:11:04.950 --> 00:11:07.203
Just kidding, but get your question right.

216
00:11:08.340 --> 00:11:10.023
AGS choosing wisely.

217
00:11:10.890 --> 00:11:14.793
Don't prescribe a medicine without conducting a drug review.

218
00:11:16.650 --> 00:11:18.930
We're all family doctors and we know this happens.

219
00:11:18.930 --> 00:11:21.060
The patient goes to all these different kind of specialists

220
00:11:21.060 --> 00:11:22.023
and gets started on all kind of things

221
00:11:22.023 --> 00:11:24.723
that we might not even know about, okay?

222
00:11:26.340 --> 00:11:28.590
Certain medicines might have been started

223
00:11:28.590 --> 00:11:32.883
to treat the side effects of other medicines, right?

224
00:11:34.020 --> 00:11:36.540
So make sure they're bringing in a med list,

225
00:11:36.540 --> 00:11:38.610
family's bringing in a med list.

226
00:11:38.610 --> 00:11:41.463
Your staff are really, really focusing on this.

227
00:11:43.410 --> 00:11:47.703
Here's our resources, Beers Criteria, START/STOPP list.

228
00:11:48.570 --> 00:11:50.910
You can plug this into your favorite search engine,

229
00:11:50.910 --> 00:11:52.953
the Anticholinergic Burden Scale.

230
00:11:54.300 --> 00:11:57.390
That's a nice tool because it will have point values

231
00:11:57.390 --> 00:11:59.550
for different kind of different medicines

232
00:11:59.550 --> 00:12:04.380
and how anticholinergic they are, which is nice.

233
00:12:04.380 --> 00:12:07.623
For instance, paroxetine,

234
00:12:09.300 --> 00:12:12.990
also known as Paxil, on the Blackwelder list of things

235
00:12:12.990 --> 00:12:15.930
he will find his family medicine residents

236
00:12:15.930 --> 00:12:18.370
if they ever start it on an older adult

237
00:12:19.350 --> 00:12:21.963
because it's so highly anticholinergic.

238
00:12:23.100 --> 00:12:25.770
I have gotten thank you notes from patients

239
00:12:25.770 --> 00:12:27.030
who come to us in rehab.

240
00:12:27.030 --> 00:12:28.290
They're there for a broken hip.

241
00:12:28.290 --> 00:12:31.770
They're there visiting their daughter from Illinois

242
00:12:31.770 --> 00:12:33.427
and they say, "No, no, no Blackwelder,

243
00:12:33.427 --> 00:12:34.357
"I don't know you.

244
00:12:34.357 --> 00:12:38.040
"I've been on paroxetine for 20 years and I do okay."

245
00:12:38.040 --> 00:12:39.877
And I say, "You know, really, let's wean it

246
00:12:39.877 --> 00:12:40.717
"while you're here.

247
00:12:40.717 --> 00:12:42.600
"Let's get off of it and try it."

248
00:12:42.600 --> 00:12:44.250
They finally buy in,

249
00:12:44.250 --> 00:12:46.900
and I get a thank you note from 'em six months later.

250
00:12:48.450 --> 00:12:49.957
And they say, "I didn't realize how much

251
00:12:49.957 --> 00:12:51.297
"that was affecting me."

252
00:12:53.130 --> 00:12:56.070
That's fun, okay?

253
00:12:56.070 --> 00:12:58.080
So add that to the list.

254
00:12:58.080 --> 00:13:00.330
Polypharmacy, five or more medications.

255
00:13:00.330 --> 00:13:01.467
You all know this.

256
00:13:01.467 --> 00:13:04.080
You're on more than that, more than four medicines,

257
00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:05.580
you raise your risk of falling

258
00:13:07.020 --> 00:13:09.150
and all kind of other bad outcomes.

259
00:13:09.150 --> 00:13:12.663
So you can total up the Anticholinergic Burden Scale score,

260
00:13:14.624 --> 00:13:17.490
and you might not be able to get people off everything,

261
00:13:17.490 --> 00:13:19.680
but if you can decrease that total score,

262
00:13:19.680 --> 00:13:24.000
you're doing patients really, really a big favor.

263
00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.150
You can print this out and hand it to them.

264
00:13:27.570 --> 00:13:28.740
Educate your staff about it,

265
00:13:28.740 --> 00:13:30.150
and your staff is gonna like...

